  "prompt": "What is Tacometer?",
  "response": "A tachometer is an instrument used to measure the rotational speed of a shaft or disk, typically in units of revolutions per minute (RPM). It is commonly found in various applications, including automotive vehicles, aircraft, and industrial machinery.\n\nIn automobiles, the tachometer provides the driver with information about the engine's RPM, helping them to optimize performance, fuel efficiency, and gear shifting. In industrial settings, tachometers can be used to monitor the speed of motors and other rotating equipment to ensure they operate within safe and efficient parameters.\n\nTachometers can be either analog or digital. Analog tachometers often use a needle on a dial to indicate speed, while digital tachometers display the RPM with numeric readings. There are also different types of tachometers, such as mechanical, electrical, and optical, each based on different principles of operation.",
